info.name: FHIR
info.description:
[HL7 FHIR](https://www.hl7.org/fhir/overview.html) is a RESTful standard for exchanging healthcare data. This is a JSON-based implementation for receiving patient data in structured (Resources) and unstructured (Binary) form.

The endpoint authentication uses OAuth2. Full instructions are provided [here](https://github.com/spe-uob/HealthcareDataLake/blob/main/api/README.md).

There are two types of interactions with the endpoint:

1. `/<Resource>/` 

  Resource can be any of the FHIR Types such as Patient, Appointment, Medication - full list [here](https://www.hl7.org/fhir/resourcelist.html#tabs-2)

2. `/Binary`
  
  Binary is for uploading files

The following documentation shows an example of using both. You can edit the language setting on this page to generate code snippets in your chosen programming language.

item.name: Resource

request.description: With a FHIR resource type of `Patient`, the `POST` request is used to create a new record.
The `PUT` request is used to create or replace a `Patient` record. In this example, we update (create a new version of) the record created in the previous example that used a `POST` request.

item.description:
The following examples have selected the `Patient` resource type, however the API supports any of the FHIR resource types - these are given by the `GET Metadata` request.

We will demonstrate the use of `POST` and `PUT` requests. `GET` and `DELETE` are not shown as they are due to be deprecated in a future version. You will not be able to directly delete or download data, only upload new data. If you overwrite an existing record using the `PUT` request, it will not actually delete the data but rather version it by leaving the previous copy marked as deleted whilst still retaining a copy and version history.

item.name: Binary

request.description:
In this example, we make a request to store a new binary object by providing metadata such as `contentType` of `image/jpeg`.

The successful response contains the parameter `putPreSignedUrl` which you then use to upload the file. If the file is less than 5 GB you can use a single `PUT` operation ([guide](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/dev/UploadingObjects.html)). For instructions on uploading multipart files with the presigned url, you can use [this guide](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/dev/PresignedUrlUploadObjectJavaSDK.html) as a starter.

In this example, we upload a new PDF file to replace the JPEG file using the ID obtained from a POST request beforehand. Notice how the response object shows that the `versionId` has incremented by 1.

item.description:
Binary resources are FHIR resources that consist of binary/unstructured data of any kind. This could be X-rays, PDF, video or other files. 

When uploading files, you use the `POST` request to store the metadata about the file and this will return a URL which you then use to `PUT` (upload) the object to.
